utterance: Hi Sam, how are you doing today?
I see that this is the first time you've come in, you've filled out some of the other paperwork.
I mean I've seen that stuff before, but it wasn't too bad.
I'm going to ask you a series of questions as part of a process called intake.
So this document that I'll be making notes on will go in your chart and it'll help guide  your care for the time that you're with me.
So these questions are going to be more detailed and more emotionally oriented than a lot of  those questions that you were answering on the forms you filled out before.
That was more like factual information that we need for insurance or record keeping.
This is more about you and what you've been going through.
If at any time you don't like one of the questions or you don't want to answer one of the questions,  just let me know and we'll just skip over that.
So what brings you in today?
Things have just not been fantastic so I figured I might as well get some help.
And you're worried they're going to get worse?
What would you say that your main problem is that motivates you to come in?
I'm just nervous about a lot of things a lot of the time and it's kind of trickling into  every area of my life now.
You said it's like a nervousness?
Yeah, just like nervousness about going places, nervousness about doing things or school or  work or you know graduating college.
Just kind of that whole stage and it's been like that for a while.
I can remember as far back as like 13 or 14 maybe.
So this is around 10 years you've been coping with this?
So there's times when you're not anxious?
I mean I'm still anxious but not as extreme or I don't deal with it in the same way.
If you were to rate your anxiety on a scale of 1 to 10 with 1 being really no anxiety  and 10 being the worst it's been in the last 10 years, how much anxiety do you have right
When was the last time you were a 10?
When was the last time you were a 1?
Maybe like a couple months ago when I was just hanging out with my friends.
We went out and we were partying a little bit and it was nice.
So the anxiety is one problem.
I don't think it's a huge problem but I have been drinking a lot.
But it helps with the anxiety but it makes going out and you know I'm more relaxed that  way.
But I can be kind of a compulsive person so once I start I keep going.
So it's not all the time.
It's just happening when I'm going out but I end up drinking too much.
So sometimes when you go out you drink more than you want to.
I make bad decisions or I get sick or the next morning I'm showing up hungover going  to class.
I take class and you know it's fun for the time being but it's not fun afterwards.
So the consequences of drinking in the longer run.
You're not too fond of those but in the short run.
So you want the anxiety to be lessened.
Do you want the drinking to be lessened?
I mean I'd like to still have fun in college but I would like to not be like blacking out  or being able to stop would be nice.
Do you remember the last time you blacked out?
It's not all the time though.
What age did you start drinking?
So those are the two main things that are bothering you.
So I want to ask you some questions about your history.
And I'm going to try to divide this up into different areas and just kind of move from  one area to the next.
So if I ask you the same question more than once it's just kind of part of that overlap  that occurs.
First I'd like to cover your family history.
So can you tell me about your immediate family?
Those are my parents really successful too.
What type of relationship do you have with your sister?
Kind of like a Merry Christmas, Happy Easter type of relationship.
We're more like acquaintances than we are siblings.
Would you describe it as distant?
We're not like, but we're not going to be like involved in each other's lives really.
Do you know what caused the relationship to end up that way?
She was always kind of the ideal child.
She went and did everything that she was supposed to do and it was easy for her.
So constantly being compared to that doesn't really foster a great relationship.
Who compared you to your sister?
Was this a frequent occurrence, the comparison?
Do you feel like it had an impact on you?
It wasn't like I wasn't trying, but not everything can be as easy as it is for some people.
So a little acknowledgement might be nice.
Alright, so let's move out a little further.
So you talked about your mother, your father, your sister.
Typical grandparents, not super involved, but they're there sometimes.
Yeah, I mean, you know, grandparents show up and it's always like,  hi, how's it going?
And you see them at the next holiday type of thing.
Alright, so there's not one grandparent you're particularly close to?
I do have one grandfather I talk to on a more personal level than I would my other ones.

I have a couple of cousins that I would hang out with or I'll see out when I'm hanging out with my friends or whatever.
So we'll hang out if we run into each other.
Aunts and uncles I do have.
They're not super involved either, but everybody's cordial.
Yeah, nice when they see you type of thing.
So when's the last time you spoke, say for example, with one of your cousins?
I think I ran into one of them only two weeks ago, or just out.
Do any of the relatives that you mentioned, are any of them aware of your anxiety and or your drinking?
My sister knows about the anxiety part of it.

But if my parents know, I'm sure she knows.
So you believe that they told her?
But she's not mentioned that to you directly?
No, we don't have those types of conversations.

So you see this bothers you?
Some of these topics that we're going to touch on in this intake, we can talk about in greater detail later on.

Alright, so, and maybe your relationship with your mother and father and your sister would be topics we could touch on later on, maybe not, but I want to let you know that we can come back to anything and review it.

Okay, how about nieces or nephews?
Any other social relationships that I've missed here that are important to you?
I don't think so, those are the main ones right now.

No other illnesses, surgeries, procedures, with no?

Alright, so you feel like you're ready to commit the treatment a little more vigorously at this point?
Yeah, I want the help now.
